# makes plots nice
def make_pretty(ax, title='', x_label='', y_label='', img=False):
    ax.set_title(title, fontsize=20)
    ax.set_xlabel(x_label, fontsize=16)
    ax.set_ylabel(y_label, fontsize=16)
    ax.legend(loc='best', fontsize=16)
    if img:
        ax.axis('off')
    return ax

Implementation of Selection and Insertion Sort¶

In [ ]:
def insertion_sort(lst):
    for j in range(1, len(lst)):
        check = lst[j]

        i = j - 1
        while i >= 0 and lst[i] > check:
            lst[i + 1] = lst[i]
            i -= 1
        lst[i + 1] = check

    return lst

        


def selection_sort(lst):
    for j in range(len(lst) - 1):
        smallest = j
        
        for i in range(j + 1, len(lst)):
            if lst[i] < lst[smallest]:
                smallest = i
        
        temp = lst[j]
        lst[j] = lst[smallest]
        lst[smallest] = temp
            

    return lst

Benchmarking function¶

In [ ]:
def benchmark_time(algo, lst):
    start = perf_counter()
    x = algo(lst)
    end = perf_counter()
    return end - start

Validating formal run times¶

Insertion Sort

from scipy.stats import linregress

# reverse case
run_times = [0.0005, 0.037, 3.95, 100.3, 406]
x = linregress(np.log([100, 1000, 10000, 50000, 100000]), np.log(run_times))

print(f'The slope of the reverse case is: {x.slope}')

# sorted case
run_times = [0.00011, 0.00012, 0.0012, 0.005, 0.0096]
x = linregress(np.log([100, 1000, 10000, 50000, 100000]), np.log(run_times))

print(f'The slope of the sorted case is: {x.slope}')

# average
run_times = [0.00025, 0.021, 2.05, 51.4, 214.9]
x = linregress(np.log([100, 1000, 10000, 50000, 100000]), np.log(run_times))

print(f'The slope of the average case is: {x.slope}')

6. Reflection Questions¶

  1. Create a table of the theoretical and estimated run time functions for the 6 combos. Do your estimates match the theory?
Selection sort (reverse sorted) Selection sort (sorted) Selection sort (random)
theor $n^2$ $n^2$ $n^2$
exper $n^2$ $n^2$ $n^2$
Insertion sort (reverse sorted) Insertion sort (sorted) Insertion sort (random)
theor $n^2$ $n$ $n^2$
exper $n^2$ $n$ $n^2$

Theoretically in insertion sort if the list is sorted in ascending order, it will never go into the inner while loop and it will simply be $O(n)$. In the worst case scenario, the list is reverse sorted and will then be $O(n^2)$. In a random ordered list, it will have to go into the inner loop not every time and will also be $O(n^2)$.

In selection sort, no matter what, it will have two complete to for loops, however as the algorithm continues the number of iterations the inner loop has to do decreases. Since there are no real optimizations for different cases, the runtimes are equivalent for all cases. Hence the runtime is $O(n^2)$ for all.

All this to say that yes the estimates match the theory.

  1. Which algorithm had a better run time than the other and for which case? Why do you think that one case was substantially faster for that algorithm? (Hint: focus on the inner loops.)

  • The insertion sort algorithm has a better runtime for the sorted case, because of the short circuiting nature of the inner while loop. The while loop has conditions on it that will stop it from looping all the way once it has found the spot to insert the element.

  • In the case where the list was initialized in random order, both algorithms performed very similaryl in runtime and there was no clear winner.

  • In the reverse sorted case the selection sort algorithm had a better runtime. Both algorithms have similar looping structures in the inner loop in that it does not always go to n. In insertion sort the first time through it only has to loop through once. In selection sort in the last time through the algorithm has to only loop through once as well. Insertion sorts inner loop goes from 1 (the first loop) to n (the last loop), while selection sort goes from n (the first loop) to 1 (the last loop). The reason why selection sort is doubly as fast as insertion sort is due to the fact that it does not switch elements from within the inner loop. Insertion sort must switch elements in the list every time it runs the while loop, while selection sort only has to switch once at the end of the outer for loop.

  1. Based on your results, which of the two sorting algorithms would you use in practice?
  • Which sorting algorithm I would use depends on the use case of the algorithm and what state the list is in when given to the sorting algorithm. If the list were already sorted for the most part and just some outliers need to be mvoed around, I would use insertion sort as this has a better runtime when using sorted lists. If the list were in reverse sorted order, I would use selection sort as this runs doubly as fast as the counterpart.
